title: Insects And Other Invertebrates Of Riddells Creek

items.title: Commius elegans
items.content_text: Lots on a Cherry Ballart (Exocarpos cupressiformis). I notice there are a few pics on the internet of this species on Exocarpos species. They are adept at hiding, by moving to the other side of the twig/branch they are on.

items.title: Rhinotia hemisticta
items.content_text: On Acacia dealbata subsp. dealbata.

items.title: Omorgus australasiae
items.content_text: Vibrates and makes a noise when touched. Last pic shows armoured plating fully down over face. Found by Ellena Best.

items.title: Netelia spp.
items.content_text: About half the size of the other common, large red Netelia wasp seen at this location. ID as Netelia spp. by Ken Walker who is also not sure it is Netelia spp.. Ken added "There are several genera (eg: Enicophilus, Ophion, Leptophion, Riekophion etc) that all have the same body shape and colour. The wing venation is the key to distinguishing these genera. I have punted for Netelia as and identification because I believe I can see a small triangular cell on the outer margins of the forewings."

items.title: Lycosa spp., Lycosidae spp.
items.content_text: Large wolf spider, about an inch long. Ventured into the house.

items.title: Ichneumonidae spp.
items.content_text: Probably same species as 12445.

items.title: Ichneumonidae spp.
items.content_text: White 'spectacles'. White socks on rear legs. White bands on antennae. In open woodland. Exhibited hunting wasp behaviour (short low flights, antennae monitoring ground activity). Same species as 12494. Very small.

items.title: Fletchamia sugdeni
items.content_text: Red tip seems to be a feature of this species. See comments.

items.title: Eurygryllodes spp.
items.content_text: I suspect this is the whistling Cricket that can be heard every night giving a lovely soft whistle. Whistles at 5200Hz which is picked up by an iPhone but not by my Samsung phone!

items.title: Zosteria spp.
items.content_text: Upper fly was landed when it caught lower fly as it flew by. Upper fly also appears to eating a moth - multi-tasking! Close-up of upper fly and moth in pic2-3.

items.title: Sceliphron laetum
items.content_text: The size of this wasp took me by surprise when it flew by - a very large wasp.

items.title: Fletchamia mediolineata
items.content_text: Sitting on a waterside log, then moved into the water. Spotted by Lydia Best. ID by LW - see comments.

items.title: Gelidea torrida
items.content_text: In Grassland area.

items.title: Diptera spp., Hydrocotyle laxiflora
items.content_text: Tiny flies over Stinking Pennywort.

items.content_text: Apparently nothing looking like this in the Museum collection.

items.title: Diamma bicolor
items.content_text: Blue Ant is actually a wasp with a big sting that feeds in flowers.

items.content_text: One of the 'spitfires'. Either P. dorsalis or P. affinis - they apparently can't be separated at the larval stage.

items.title: Cercophonius squama
items.content_text: These scorpions hide under bark and in cracks in the wood and go walk about during the evening. In Melbourne and surrounds they are often moved into the house via firewood.

items.content_text: Assumed female - pics of female on Padil have black stripe on red thorax.

items.title: Megalyra shuckardi
items.content_text: Now that's an ovipositor! Apparently body length about 2cm, ovipositor length about 8cm! ID by Ken Walker, who added "these wasps mainly parasitise wood-boring beetles."

items.title: Cillibus incisus
items.content_text: A type of Pie-dish Beetle.

items.title: Megachile ferox
items.content_text: Red-bottomed bee! This is in the group of leafcutter/resin bees.

items.title: Diamma bicolor
items.content_text: Despite the name it is a parasitic wasp. Females are wingless & often seen wandering on the ground looking for mole crickets. They lay an egg on the paralysed cricket, with the cricket then being used as food for the developing wasp larva.

items.title: Laxta granicollis
items.content_text: Female. Lurking under bark. Not 100% sure of ID but, given a male was found at this site later (see 9121), chances are very good they are the same species.

items.title: Laxta granicollis
items.content_text: Male. Wandering on concrete verandah.

items.content_text: Ants are attending the pupae.

items.title: Amphibolia spp., Leptomyrmex erythrocephalus
items.content_text: Spider Ant dragging away a fly of the Amphibolia genus. No date available - would likely be a summer interaction.

items.title: Callomelitta picta
items.content_text: A beautifully coloured bee. Possibly a male as the female on Padil seems to have a black band on the predominantly red back.

items.title: Paralastor spp.
items.content_text: A wasp that looks like a wasp mimic - a double bluff? :)

items.title: Amphylaeus (Amphylaeus) morosus

items.title: Tryonocryptus gigas
items.content_text: This one was flying around just above the ground like a spider wasp. ID by Ken Walker.

items.title: Leptomyrmex erythrocephalus, Myrmecia pilosula
items.content_text: Watched the Red-headed Ant overcome the Jumping Jack and then carry it off.

items.title: Turneromyia bassiana
items.content_text: Keys out to Turneromyia bassiana.

items.title: Phlebopus marginatus, Tapeigaster cinctipes
items.content_text: Possibly the first time this fly species has been photographed & the first time the female (left) has been associated with the male. They moved to the 'dancing' position briefly then the male moved away. ID by Ken Walker. (see also observation 8834).

items.title: Porismus strigatus
items.content_text: In reasonably large numbers on tree trunks near Barringo Creek - some paired off, head to head, as though competing. Hot and humid and rumbling thunder nearby.

items.title: Williamsita (Androcrabro) bivittata
items.content_text: Spent some time flying around the developing seeds of Bursaria spinosa subsp. spinosa.

items.title: Hemiptera spp.
items.content_text: Large numbers, often paired up, in Senecio glomeratus.

items.title: Chauliognathus lugubris
items.content_text: A plague of Plague Soldier Beetles.

items.title: Cercopoidea spp.
items.content_text: Possibly a bug peeping/emerging? An inquisitive soldier beetle above. Don't know what the black secretion is?

items.title: Gminatus australis, Senecio linearifolius var. linearifolius
items.content_text: On Senecio linearifolius var. linearifolius. A carnivorous insect that lives among flowers. Glyphipterix chrysoplanetis is the tiny moth in the 2nd pic that might be on the menu for the Assassin Bug?

items.content_text: On the wall in the downstairs loo.

items.title: Cercopoidea spp.
items.content_text: On Acacia melanoxylon. The spit-like substance is encasing some little hoppers.

items.title: Unidentified
items.content_text: On Mistletoe, Amyema pendula. Could be Mistletoe Moth but can't find info on pupae.

items.title: Leptotarsus (Macromastix) spp.

items.title: Peltoschema orphana
items.content_text: On A. mearnsii. Many plants in the area dead or defoliated. Many still healthy too. In this this area A. leprosa var. uninervia is also being seriously damaged or killed (apparently by a very similar but different species).

items.title: Peltoschema orphana
items.content_text: This small A. mearnsii plant was covered in beetles.

items.title: Peltoschema orphana
items.content_text: On Acacia mearnsii - plant only defoliated a small amount but mearnsii all but disappeared from this location a couple of years ago. A few new plants returned last year and this year. On the volcanic plains.

items.title: Acacia leprosa var. uninervia, Peltoschema orphana
items.content_text: What looks like Fireblight Beetle attacking Acacia leprosa. All plants at this spot seem to be dead or seriously damaged. Two individuals photographed.

items.title: Calomela parilis
items.content_text: On Acacia dealbata subsp. dealbata. ID by Chris Read, via Ken Walker.

items.title: Tipulidae spp.
items.content_text: Lots of these flying on a bright sunny day in May. Bluish colouring seemed to be a feature.

items.title: Talaurinus impressicollis
items.content_text: Large beetle. ID by SJ.

items.title: Delta bicinctus
items.content_text: Orange Potter Wasp (lives near water, required for pot making). Seems to be distinguished from Delta latreillei latreillei by a three striped abdomen (orange-black-orange, only black-orange in latreillei) and different black & orange pattern on thorax.

items.title: Cryptocheilus bicolor
items.content_text: Spider-hunting wasp with prey. Pulled it along ground and down crack in clay pictured in 2nd photo. They are often seen flying/patrolling just above the ground. ID by Ken Walker.

items.title: Tiphiidae spp.
items.content_text: Female is wingless. Adults feed on nectar. Female burrows into the ground, parasitising beetle larvae & mole crickets. They are important pollinators of native plants. Females sometimes mistaken for ants. (adapted from ABC website)

items.title: Paropsisterna variicollis
items.content_text: Photos taken over 2 years. Assumed they are all the same species - all photos taken within a few metres on the same tree - Eucalyptus aromaphloia.

items.title: Fabriogenia spp.
items.content_text: Yellow antennae black spider wasp.

items.title: Lehmannia nyctelia
items.content_text: Inside the house. Possibly the culprit that shorted a plug that knocked out electricity to half the house a few months ago.

items.title: Paropsisterna variicollis
items.content_text: I assume these two pics are the same species. They are on the same plant close to each other, and on the same plant/location as obs 2072 last year. On Eucalyptus aromaphloia.

items.title: Unidentified
items.content_text: Millions have emerged, especially seen covering low plants near creek, especially grasses but not exclusively. Second pic is on a Senecio minimus leaf.
